					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2000367&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164135" alt="WrongJohnSilver" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2000367)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;" >WrongJohnSilver</a></span> <span class="odate time_1517418985 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Jan 2018 17:16</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3696848">
									

<p>Yeah, I made up the worm-that-walks conspiracy for the purpose of the logs, because I figured it would be important to include something that <em>didn't</em> appear to have a real-world analog to make readers think they're looking at something that is anomalous.</p>
<p>Wicca? Nukes? Not anomalous, they're out in the public, we all know they're there.</p>
<p>Worm-that-walks? &#8230;Not nearly as well known as a concept, and never heard of as a conspiracy&#8230; so, coverup? Non-event? Is there an anomaly or not? Hard to reach that ambiguous point where you can't really say, &quot;Yup, that's an anomaly, all right,&quot; but you also can't say, &quot;Nope, that's not an anomaly, it's just a crackpot theory.&quot;</p>

							</div>

								
					
