					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/agentwilson" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(802114); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=802114&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164136" alt="AgentWilson" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=802114)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/agentwilson" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(802114); return false;" >AgentWilson</a></span> <span class="odate time_1510178655 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Nov 2017 22:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3628648">
									

<p>One of the things that I like about how this particular article is written is that it treats anomalies like they are inexplicable and rare, as opposed to many more recent ones where entire new fields of science have been built up where we are still considering certain things to be &quot;anomalous&quot; despite knowing almost everything about their origins, behavior, and mechanics.</p>
<p>Something I'd like to do at some point is write an article about an anomaly that doesn't have an associated drop in the local Hume field and can't be contained with SRAs. It makes it seem more like a form of science unknown to the world at large but kept behind lock and key by sanctimonious know-it-alls.</p>

							</div>

								
					
